[1]
Date: Thu 22 Nov 2007
Source: Eurosurveillance Weekly Release, 22 Nov 2007 [edited]
<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ew/2007/071122.asp#5>


Outbreak of norovirus gastroenteritis among staff at a hospital in
Barcelona, Spain, September 2007
------------------------------------------------------------------------
-------------------------------------------------------
On 14 Sep 2007, an outbreak of acute gastroenteritis was reported
among health care workers (HCW) employed at a hospital in Barcelona,
Spain. The Infection Control Team (ICT) at the hospital was informed
that several HCW had become suddenly ill, suffering nausea, vomiting
and diarrhoea (without blood, pus or mucus in the stool) since 10 Sep 2007.

The working hypothesis was that meals at the hospital restaurant were
related to the cause of the outbreak. We designed an unmatched
case-control study, following standard operation procedures for
foodborne outbreak investigation. We collected preliminary basic data
and inspected the department premises in order to identify the source
and the likely pathogen of this outbreak. All HCW reporting vomiting
and/or diarrhoea who had lunch or dinner at the hospital restaurant
between 10 and 14 Sep 2007 were classified as cases. Available cases
were interviewed, either personally or by phone, using a structured
questionnaire. We collected data on the time and type of food
consumed at the hospital restaurant. Frozen samples from all meals
offered by the restaurant to HCW staff in this time period were
collected from the kitchen. Stool samples were available only from 4
cases, and were collected for microbiological analysis.

A total of 38 cases were identified and 31 of them were interviewed.
The remaining 7 cases could not be reached during the initial phases
of the study or declined to answer the questionnaire. We also
interviewed 31 unmatched HCW selected as controls among other staff
employed in the same departments and who also ate regularly at the
hospital restaurant. The age of cases ranged from 29 to 59 years. The
controls were between 24 and 63 years of age. Reported symptoms were
abdominal pain (n=27; 87 percent), nausea (n=25; 81 percent), watery
diarrhoea (n=24; 77 percent), vomiting (n=22; 71 percent), headache
(n=11; 35 percent) and low-grade fever (n=4; 13 percent). The disease
was mild in most cases. Only 4 cases sought medical advice, but none
was admitted to hospital. Symptoms lasted from four to 72 hours.

A total of 24 HCW affected by the outbreak do not have direct contact
with the patients in the hospital, because they work in support
services (laboratory, administration). All cases but one eat
regularly at the hospital's restaurant. There were no cases detected
among patients admitted at the hospital. The majority of cases (n=23)
occurred between 13 and 14 Sep 2007. There were no cases after 16
September. The earliest reported onset of symptoms was 8 Sept 2007.
This case and another one who fell ill on 13 Sep 2007 but for whom
the exact time of onset of symptoms is unknown are not included in
the epidemic curve (presented as a figure in the original test) but
we decided to include them in the outbreak investigation.

All types of food exposure were analysed by means of a logistic
regression technique, using as dependent variables being case or
control and as independent variables having eaten or not a particular
type of food. Cross tabs for all types of food were also performed.
HCW who reported to have eaten rice salad with cocktail sauce were
more likely to have become sick compared to HCW who did not eat rice
salad with cocktail sauce. (OR=4,11; CI95:1,14-14,72; p=0,03). A
waterborne source was ruled out (OR=0,675 CI95 percent:0,237-1,924).
Statistical analyses indicated that 12 Sep 2007 (the day when the
rice salad with cocktail sauce was served) was the most likely
starting date of the outbreak (OR day 12= 3,37 (p=0,07) vs OR day
10=0,56 (p=0,32)).

Norovirus was identified in 2 of the 4 stool samples available for
laboratory analysis. One of the 4 samples was taken from a staff
member working at the hospital's restaurant but it was negative. All
meals tested negative for bacteria, but were not analysed for
norovirus, because in Barcelona this testing is not routinely
performed on food.

The hypothesis that the outbreak was foodborne was confirmed by the
results of the epidemiological analysis and by the identification of
norovirus in 2 stool samples taken from cases. We believe that
norovirus contamination of rice salad with cocktail sauce was the
cause of the outbreak. Noroviruses are considered to be the most
frequent etiologic agents of food- and water-borne viral
gastroenteritis outbreaks [1]. A few outbreaks affecting hospital
staff have already been described [2,3]. It is likely that the
outbreak reported here was foodborne, caused by the contamination of
rice salad with cocktail sauce by norovirus and its further
dissemination. It is possible that the staff member working at the
restaurant (onset of symptoms on 8 Sep 2007) was the index case,
although his stool samples were negative for norovirus.

We believe that patients admitted to the hospital were not affected
by the outbreak because they did not share the same meals as offered
to HCW by the kitchen service. Fortunately, on 12 Sep 20007, the
patients had stew chickpeas and roasted chicken as lunch menu. They
did not have the choice of salad with cocktail sauce which we believe
to have caused the outbreak. The basic hygiene preventive measures
(notably hand washing) seemed to have worked well enough to help
further control the outbreak, probably because of the low likelihood
of direct contact between the affected HCW and patients.

(By L Costas (lcostas@clinic.ub.es)1, A Vilella1, A Llupia1, J
Bosch2, MT Jimenez de Anta2, A Trilla1 Preventive Medicine and
Epidemiology Department1, Microbiology Department2, Hospital Clinic,
Barcelona, Spain)

References
-------------
(1) Thornton AC, Jennings-Conklin KS, McCormick MI. Noroviruses:
agents in outbreaks of acute gastroenteritis. Disaster Manag
Response. 2004 Jan-Mar;2(1):4-9.

(2) Outbreak of acute gastroenteritis among emergency department
staff. Emerg Med J. 2007 Oct;24(10):699-702. Nosocomial outbreak of
norovirus gastroenteritis and investigation of ABO histo-blood group
type in infected staff and patients. J Hosp Infect. 2004 Oct;58(2):163-4.

(3) Nosocomial outbreak of norovirus gastroenteritis and
investigation of ABO histo-blood group type in infected staff and
patients. J Hosp Infect. 2004 Oct;58(2):163-4.

